ernment structures; the recuperation of former communist farming entities by former managers; and the transformation of peasants into rural citizens, who nevertheless remain the underdogs. Swain exposes common features as well as specific divergences between the six countries; he portrays the winners, losers and engineers of transformations. He situates his themes in a wider context that will appeal to a broad range of social scientists and historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAgriculture and statexEurope, Eastern. 0aAgriculture and statezEurope, Eastern. 0aDemocratizationxEurope, Eastern. 0aDemocratizationzEurope, Eastern. 0aPost-communismxEurope, Eastern. 0aPost-communismzEurope, Eastern. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAgriculture, Democratization, Eastern Europe, Economic conditions, Political economy, Regime change.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615522571040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155225710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155225710/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK